BLUETONGUE - EUROPE (22): HUNGARY (CSONGRAD) REQUEST FOR INFORMATION
********************************************************************
A ProMED-mail post
http://www.promedmail.org
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
http://www.isid.org

Date: Tue 14 Oct 2014
Source: Press release, Hungary's National Food Chain Safety Office [in Hungarian, machine trans. summarised, edited]
https://www.nebih.gov.hu/aktualitasok/hirek/Magyarorszagon_is_megjelent_a_keknyelv_betegseg.html


The National Food Chain Safety Office (NEBIH) reports that bluetongue has been recorded in ruminants in the southern county of Csongrad. The disease has been diagnosed by the national bluetongue reference laboratory.

Since the end of September 2014, surveillance measures have been applied in the southern districts of Csongrad and Bekes in view of the disease spreading in adjacent areas in southern Europe. The virus has been recorded by the NEBIH laboratory in samples from 2 farms. Consequently, protection and surveillance zones have been officially established and animal movement prohibition applied on the affected farms.

Farmers are requested to report any suspected case immediately to their practitioner or to the district veterinary office (contact addresses provided).

--
Communicated by:
Sabine Zentis
Castleview English Longhorns
