[For the location of Csongrad, see map at http://www.fallingrain.com/world/HU/06/Csongrad.html. The region is close to Hungary's border with Romania and Serbia, both known to be infected by BTV-4. Romania's BTV-4 restriction zones extend to territories beyond its borders, in southeastern Hungary. This can be seen in slide 6 of Romania's National Sanitary Veterinary & Food Safety Authority (NSVFSA) presentation to the SCFCAH [Standing Committee on the Food Chain and Animal Health], dated 6 Oct 2014:
http://ec.europa.eu/food/committees/regulatory/scfcah/animal_health/docs/2014100607_bt_romania.pdf.

Further details, including species affected, morbidity/mortality figures, and serotyping results, are anticipated to be included in the due notification to the OIE. - Mod.AS

A HealthMap/ProMED-mail map can be accessed at: https://promedmail.org/promed-post?place=2864198,112.]
